Q2: An electrical manufacturing company conducts quality checks at specified periods on the products it manufactures. Historically, the failure rate for the manufactured item is 5%. Suppose a random sample of 10 manufactured items is selected. Answer the following questions¶

2.1 Probability that none of the items are defective?

This is an example of a binomial event where the products can either be defective or not defective.

p = P(sample is defective) = 5% = 0.05
n = Number of samples = 10

Hence the probability distribution for this can be obtained via the stats.binom.pmf or stats.binom.cdf functions with n=10 and p=0.05, depending on whether we need cumulative or point probability

In mathematical terms, the formula would be given as below for the probability of getting x defective items, for a given n & p

$$ P(X=x) = \binom{n}{x}p^x (1-p)^{n-x} $$
In [3]:

2.3 Probability that two or fewer of the items are defective?

Probability that two or fewer of the items is defective = Probability (0 defective or 1 defective or 2 defectives)
Since, these are mutually exclusive events,
Probability that two or fewer of the items is defective = Probability (0 defective) + Probability (1 defective) + Probability (2 defectives)

Q3: A car salesman sells on an average 3 cars per week.¶

3.1 Probability that in a given week he will sell some cars

This experiment, with no restriction on the maximum number of "trials/events" can be described by Poisson Distribution.

lambda = Average sales rate = 3 cars/week
Hence the probability distribution for this can be obtained via the stats.poisson.pmf or stats.poissonm.cdf functions with lambda=3, depending on whether we need cumulative or point probability

In mathematical terms, the formula would be given as below for the probability of selling x cars in a week, for a given $\lambda$

$$ P(X=x) = \frac{\lambda^x e^{-\lambda}}{x!} $$

Hence the probability distribution for this can be obtained via the stats.binom.pmf or stats.binom.cdf functions with n=3 and p=0.868, depending on whether we need cumulative or point probability

In mathematical terms, the formula would be given as below for the probability of getting x orders correct, for a given n & p

$$ P(X=x) = \binom{n}{x}p^x (1-p)^{n-x} $$

Q5: A group of 300 professionals sat for a competitive exam. The results show the information of marks obtained by them have a mean of 60 and a standard deviation of 12. The pattern of marks follows a normal distribution. Answer the following questions¶

5.1 What is the percentage of students who score more than 80.

As mentioned in the question, this is a normal distribution with

loc = mean = 60
scale = standard deviation = 12

Hence, the probability distribution can be obtained by using stats.norm.cdf function, as per the value mentioned

In mathematical terms, the formula would be given as below for the probability mass function is given by, for a given $\mu$ and $\sigma$ $$f(x) = \frac{1}{\sigma\sqrt{2\pi}} \exp\left( -\frac{1}{2}\left(\frac{x-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{\!2}\,\right) $$

In [13]:
loc = 60
scale =12
print ("Percentage of students scored > 80 = %0.2f%%" %((1-stats.norm.cdf(80,loc,scale))*100))

Percentage of students scored > 80 = 4.78%

5.2 What is the percentage of students who score less than 50

In [14]:
print ("Percentage of students scored < 50 = %0.2f%%" %(stats.norm.cdf(50,loc,scale)*100))

Percentage of students scored < 50 = 20.23%

5.3 What should be the distinction mark if the highest 10% of students are to be awarded distinction?

Highest 10% of students implies we need to find the z10 that will corresponding to P(z>z10)=10%. For this, we can use the inverse distribution function

Q6: Explain 1 real life industry scenario [other than the ones mentioned above] where you can use the concepts learnt in this module of Applied statistics to get a data driven business solution.¶

The concept of Bayes Theorem can be very well applied to Spam Filters for e-mail. The filters fundamentally follow Bayes Theorem in detecting if a mail is spam or not basis the words contained in the e-mail. As per Bayes Theorem, the below probabilities will be available apriori basis sample data

P(Spam) = probability that a given e-mail is spam (based on hisotrical data)
P(Word|Spam) = probabiity that a given word occurs in a spam e-mail
P(Ham) = probability that a given e-mail is not spam (ham ; based on historical data)
P(Word|Ham) = probaility that a given word occurs in ham e-mail

From Bayes Theorem, we know that $$ P(Spam|Word) = \frac{P(Word|Spam)*P(Spam)}{P(Word)}\\ $$

We also know that since an e-mail being spam or ham are mutually exclusive events $$ P(Word) = {P(Word\cap Spam) + P(Word\cap Ham)}\\ $$

which in turn can be written as $$ P(Word) = {P(Word|Spam)*P(Spam) + P(Word|Ham)*P(Ham)} $$

Hence, $$ P(Spam|Word) = \frac{P(Word|Spam)*P(Spam)}{P(Word|Spam)*P(Spam)+P(Word|Ham)*P(Ham)}\\ $$

The data on the apriori probabilities can also be updated as we process more and more e-mails in the above system. By setting a probability threshold, we can classify e-mails as Spam or Ham. Therefore, just by knowing hte proportions of overall e-mails that are spam and ham, along with the probability of a particular word occuring in them, we can assign probability to and classify mails as Spam or Ham.

Part 2: Project Based¶

Domain: Sports

Context: Company X manages the men's top professional basketball division of the American league system. The dataset contains information on all the teams that have participated in all the past tournaments. It has data about how many baskets each team scored, conceded, how many times they came within the first 2 positions, how many tournaments they have qualified, their best position in the past, etc.

Data Description: Basketball.csv - The data set contains information on all the teams so far participated in all the past tournaments.

Attribute Information:

  1. Team: Team's name
  2. Tournament: Number of played tournaments
  3. Score: Team's score so far
  4. PlayedGames: Games played by the team so far
  5. WonGames: Games won by the team so far
  6. DrawnGames: Games drawn by the team so far
  7. LostGames: Games lost by the team so far
  8. BasketScored: Basket scored by the team so far
  9. BasketGiven: Basket scored against the team so far
  10. TournamentChampion: How many times the team was a champion of the tournaments so far
  11. Runner-up: How many times the team was a runners-up of the tournaments so far
  12. TeamLaunch: Year the team was launched on professional basketball
  13. HighestPositionHeld: Highest position held by the team amongst all the tournaments played

Project Objective: Company’s management wants to invest on proposal on managing some of the best teams in the league. The analytics department has been assigned with a task of creating a report on the performance shown by the teams. Some of the older teams are already in contract with competitors. Hence Company X wants to understand which teams they can approach which will be a deal win for them.

In [28]:
def comb2single(x):
    if 'to' in x:
        return x.split('to')[0]
    elif '-' in x:
        return x.split('-')[0]
    elif '~' in x:
        return x.split('~')[0]
    elif '_' in x:
        return x.split('_')[0]
    else:
        return x

df1["YearLaunch"] = df1["TeamLaunch"].apply(comb2single)
df1 = df1.astype({"YearLaunch": np.int64}) # convert YearLaunch to datatype int
today = date.today()
df1["Age"] = df1["YearLaunch"].apply(lambda x: today.year-x) # subtract YearLaunch from current year to get team age

We note the following from the correlation heat-map and the pair-plots:

  • HighestPositionHeld is inversely correalted with Win_Percent, BasketDiff, Podium_Fin, SPG as well as TourPercent
  • Podium_Fin is also correlated to Win_Percent, BasketDiff and SPG
  • Teams aged older than 40 are the ones that have achieved HighestPositionHeld < 5(except one). They also have the best Win_Percent and Podium_Fin and played most tournaments
  • As teams play more games (PlayedGames/Tournament) the chances of success (HighestPositionHed/Podium_Fin) also increase, which is understandable as the teams will get better and adapt to the tournament better with exposure
  • BasketDiff is >0 for teams that have held high positions or finished on the podium atleast once. It is also positively correlated with Win_Percent and inversely with HighestPositionHeld
  • Win_Percent is high (>30%) for teams which have held high positions or finished on the podium atleast once
  • Teams with HighestPositionHeld <5 tend to have have SPG > 1.0
  • There are many teams that, though were launched in the early years have not played as many tournaments. We see that higher the Tour_Percent, higher the Win_Percent, BasketDiff and Podium_Fin. This implies that regular participation in tournament is essential to success
  • Among teams with Age < 50, there are very few there is only 1 team which has held finished in Top 5 ever but a good number of teams have finished in Top 10

Hence, for our recommendation process flow, we note that:

  • Characteristics are distinct for older and newer teams. Newer teams take time to achieve high positions on the table. Hence, our approach should be different for older teams and emerging teams
  • Also, we see that chances of success increase with more games. We should track teams who play regularly in the tournament. Hence, we should establish a cut-off on the Tour_Percent as well.

Summary:
The aim for this exercise was to analyse the performance of multiple teams to come up with potential sponsorship candidates for Company X. To address this, the data was first cleaned to remove null values and year entry formats were standardised. The dataset contained information on teams that have taken part in the history of the tournament, number of tournaments they have taken part in, point scored, basket scored for and against, games played and their outcomes, highest position achieved, number of top 2 finishes and year of launch.

Four performance measures were introduced as derived measures such as SPG (Score Per Game), Podium_Fin (% of podium finishes over tournaments played), BasketDiff (per game difference between basket scored and given), Win_Percent(% of games won over total games) and Tour_Percent(% of age in years the team has played tournaments). These metrices are directly correlated to securing high positions in the tournaments. These measures are also essential since these are ratios and hence account for dispartiy between older and emerging teams since older teams will have higher absolute values across metrics.

Next, univariate and multivariate analyses were performed where distinct gaps were identified between older (>43 years) and emerging teams. It was also noted, that higher Tour_Percent leads to greater success, meaning that it is not the age alone that determines chance of success in future but also how regularly the team has played in those years. Hence, criteria to segregate potential candidates for older and emerging teams was finalized and the list of candidates finalised.

From here, since there are multiple metrices that could identify as successful performance, top 3 performers across various success metrices were identifed and the final recommendation list was drawn. The recommendation to Company X is to invest in any of the above teams. Teams 21 and 25 are emerging teams which have future potential. Teams 4, 6 and 11 are relatively older but best performers on multiple attributes.

Observations on the datapoints collected to perform a better data analysis¶

Quality:

  • Pre-processed data will help save time for analysis (such as launch year without combinations, the derived attributes used in the calculation, using the right data type for storage)
  • Additional data points such as Team Budgets, Head to Head records, individual match data for tournaments, Fan base, Time Since Last Appearance in tournament are useful attributes that can be captured
  • Tournament level data such as the position attained in each tournament in chornological sequence will help with accounting for recent form

Quantity:

  • For any metric there are only 61 data points available, if we take a cut on any attribute, then there are very few datapoints left to do any significance analysis/
  • The data could be made richer by adding individual match data from each of the tournaments

Variety:

  • Data from a variety of sources such as P&L statements, could be tracked to update our database
  • Specifically data on Social Media fan following, Budget, etc could help assess the customer reach and RoI that Company X can target
  • Data from specialist Basketball analytics companies such as Opta could be incorporated into this to add more attributes for anlysis

Velocity:

  • The data could be updated for each match within a tournament to provide more data points for analysis.
  • If we collect data frequently, we will also know updated information on the Operating Status of the teams, if any have stopped operations

Veracity:

  • For a Basketball dataset, there are very high number of drawn games. This questions the authenticity of the data
  • For Team 23, the PlayedGames does not equal the sum of games won, drawn and lost. This again, makes us doubt the veracity of the data

Value:

  • If we are able to implement the above successfully, we can then add value by being able to predict which teams among the candidates is best by comparing Head to Head performances and recent trends
  • We will be able to predict energing teams better if we have the information on trends and years since last appearance in the tournament.

Part 3: Project Based¶

Domain: Startup Ecosystem

Context: Company X is a EU online publisher focusing on the startups industry. The company specifically reports on the business related to technology news, analysis of emerging trends and profiling of new tech businesses and products. Their event i.e. Startup Battlefield is the world’s pre-eminent startup competition. Startup Battlefield features 15-30 top early stage startups pitching top judges in front of a vast live audience, present in person and online.

  5. Result: Described by Contestant, Finalist, Audience choice, Winner or Runner up
  6. OperatingState: Current status of the company, Operating ,Closed, Acquired or IPO

Project Objective: Analyse the data of the various companies from the given dataset and perform the tasks that are specified in the below steps. Draw insights from the various attributes that are present in the dataset, plot distributions, state hypotheses and draw conclusions from the dataset.

The distributions look very similar on the plot. However, to test the statistical significance, we will do a statistical test. We can perform two-sample z or t test here. Also, though the distributions are not normal, since our sample size > 30 we can perform the z-test or t-test.

Ho = Null Hypothesis = There is no difference between the two means (mean of funds raised by Operating and Closed)
Ha = Alternate Hypothesis = There is significant difference between the two means

Now, let us perform the z-test on this sample at 0.05 significance level

In [101]:
import scipy.stats as stats
from statsmodels.stats.weightstats import ztest
alpha = 0.05 # defining the significance level
operating = startup1[startup1['OperatingState']=='Operating']['Funds_in_million']
closed = startup1[startup1['OperatingState']=='Closed']['Funds_in_million']
z_stat, p_val = ztest(operating, closed)

if p_val > alpha:
    print("Since p_val = %.3f is greater than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is not significant \nand we fail to reject Ho" %p_val)
else:
    print("Since p_val = %.3f is less than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is significant \nand we reject Ho" %p_val)

Since p_val = 0.192 is greater than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is not significant 
and we fail to reject Ho
In [102]:
#Using t-test also gives the same result
from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
t_stat, p_val = ttest_ind(operating, closed)
if p_val > alpha:
    print("Since p_val = %.3f is greater than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is not significant \nand we fail to reject Ho" %p_val)
else:
    print("Since p_val = %.3f is less than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is significant \nand we reject Ho" %p_val)

Since p_val = 0.193 is greater than the significance level (0.05), the difference between the means is not significant

Summary:
In this analysis, the objective was to perform analyses and draw statistical conclusions on certain hypotheses. The dataset contains a list of companies along with the product for which funds were raised at various events. The data includes company name, product name, funds raised, event name, competition result and operating state. First, the data set was loaded and entries with missing values for Product and Funding were dropped from the dataset. The funding attribute was skewed and hence the outliers above the upper fence were dropped for further analysis. The funding attribute also had to be standardised in a numerical format for further processing.

Post data visualization, the aim was to check if there was significant difference between funds raised by companies that were in operating state and closed state. Using z-test at 5% significance level, it was found that there was no significant difference between the two

Next, the aim was to check if proportion of winners that are operating and proportion of contests that are operating are statistically different. Using two sample z-test at 5% significance level, it weas found that there is indeed statistically significant difference between the two.

Lastly, the aim was to check if the region of fund raise has any influence on the average funds raised by companies post 2013, among Disrupt events. Using one-way ANOVA at 5% significance level, it was concluded that there was no statistical difference between the mean funds raised between the regions NY, SF and EU.

Observations on the datapoints collected to perform a better data analysis¶

Quality:

  • We had to discard 216 entries due to unavailable data, resulting in a reduced usable data set.
  • Pre-processed data will help save time for analysis (such as capturing Event location, Year, and Funds in separate columns and in the right format
  • There are 6 event entries still missing which cannot be filled because the year or type of events are not deductible
  • Hence, complete data sets would be beneficial to perform statistical analyses
  • Specifically, data on the P&L status, employee strength, geographic presence, and a more frequently updated Funding and OperatingState will be helpful

Quantity:

  • The overall usable data is very low. Hypothesis testing is effective with higher sample sizes. When we apply filtered cuts on the data, the sample size tends to go close to the 30 cut-off, thereby affecting our normality assumptions. Hence, we shoud try to collect more data amongst each cut that we want to analyse that is representative of the population
  • In fact, if we want to test our hypothesis on individual Winner classes, it won't be possible since a few have < 30 samples

Variety:

  • Data from a variety of sources such as blog aritcles, press releases, etc could be tracked to update our database
  • Specifically data on P&L statements, Social Media activity/posts from the company, Press Releases and its contents could provide added information on the company's health and funding

Velocity:

  • The data could be updated every 3 months to ensure the 'OperationsState' and 'Funding' attributes are mapped accurately

Veracity:

  • The funding values are skewed and abnormal to another 60 outliers which could not be used for analysis. Hence, we should double-check the funding values to ensure the data is truthful and without error

Value:

  • If we are able to implement the above successfully, we can then add value by being able to predict if a company was about to Close down.
  • Movement in company employee strength, shrinkage/expansion in geographic presence can also be used to predict the OperatingState
  • Basis their P&L statements and press releases we could also predict their performance in upcoming events
